Which group should ‘Prosper’ target to maximize profit?

                                                              by JINSOO KIM

Introduction

What is ‘Prosper’?
Prosper was founded in 2005 as the first peer-to-peer lending marketplace in the United States. Since then, Prosper has facilitated more than $12 billion in loans to more than 770,000 people. If you want more details, check this link(https://www.prosper.com/home/about).

The initial dataframe provides Prosper data that was made from Nov 2005 to Mar 2014. Analyzing this dataframe by univariate, bivariate, and multivariate plots, I would like to find some insights to maximize profit.

To maximize total profit I would have basic assumptions.

  1. Marketing resources(time and money) are limited.
  2. According to #1 assumption, Prosper should narrow the targeting groups.
  3. Each variable can be narrowed to 5 factors.
  4. Buoyant market, groups are more prone to make additional profitable loans.

  2. To predict, using recent data only is better than with a big pausing gap Plus, the shape and number of loans are quite different.

1. OnTimeProsperPayments , 2. ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate

By checking above variables, I would be able to predict people can pay back(On time or late but less than one month) or not.

Before investigating two variables, need to see the entire data. Many of them do not have prior loan records. Therefore, this is only valid analysis for the people who had the loan records.

The ratio of “RightTimePayments” will be considered as we can trust the people would pay the bill.

2-11 Univariate Analysis

1) Structure of this dataset

This dataset consists of 81 variables and 113,937 loans. Some of ListingKeys are duplicated.Therefore I removed them. 81 variables are quite a lot. Some variables are related, others are not. I chose 8 variables to make better profits.

2) What are main features of this dataset?

  • There is a big pausing gap from end of 2008 to end of 2009. I thought recent 4 years record will be enough for analysis, so removed pausing gap part of this data.

  • Loans by Occupation, Purpose of borrowing, region, IncomeRange show that loans are dominated by specific groups.

  • LenderYield and LoanOriginalAmount are key variables for profit. And they are not seperate, so I made “RightTimePayments” variable to measure at once.

6. Reflection

6-1 Data wrangling.

This dataset is very clean I think. I only removed some data before specific time.

6-2 Variables I considered.

Occupation: the number, average profit, total profits of each occupation varies.

Reasons to borrow money: the number, average profit, total profits of each reason varies.

Region: the number, total profits of each region varies.

ProsperScore and ProsperRating are in strong positive relationship.

6-3 Final decision

In reality, company has to choose what work to do and not. So, I found narrowing group is needed for targeting group. Finally, I would focus on 5 states(CA, NY, TX, FL, IL) and Debt Consolidation loans.

6-4 Limit of this dataset

  1. Most of loan users do not have prior records, this means we cannot guarantee how much portion of them will pay back.

  2. For occupation, ‘Other’ takes the highest portion. This may affect Top 5 occupations that have high total profits.

  3. Debt Consolidation is the main reason to make loans. This means customers’ loans are revolving. They might find other credit companies to pay back Prosper’s loan. This pattern may end up making them bankrupt someday. So, even though Prosper focus on marketing on Debt Consolidation, it has to care about the default risk.
